(* Content-type: application/vnd.wolfram.mathematica *)

Notebook[{

Cell["Exact certificate for a candidate qutrit counterexample to the CQC conjecture", "Title"],

Cell["\
The complementary-quantum correlation (CQC) conjecture [Schneeloch, \
Broadbent, Howell, Phys. Rev. A 90, 062119 (2014); arXiv:1404.6496] asserts \
that for any bipartite state rho_AB and local pairs of mutually unbiased \
observables (Z^A, X^A), (Z^B, X^B),

    I(Z^A:Z^B) + I(X^A:X^B) <= I(A:B),

where the left side holds classical mutual informations of measurement \
outcomes and the right side is the quantum mutual information I(A:B) = S(A) \
+ S(B) - S(AB).  The conjecture was proven for pure states, for states with \
one maximally mixed subsystem, and for minimally disturbing measurements, \
and was still described as open in Iqbal, Quantum Inf. Process. 25, 250 \
(2026); arXiv:2509.08286.

This notebook is a self-contained counterexample certificate generated in \
the same GPT-5.6 Pro-assisted workflow as the repository's Python checks.  It \
is a structurally separate implementation, not independent expert review.  \
Its core certificate is exact; the final Holevo-information consistency check \
uses 40-digit eigensystems.  All logarithms are base 2, and expected outputs are \
stated in the text before each input cell.  Conventions: a two-qutrit ket |a b> is stored as a \
9-vector with index 3a + b (a, b = 0, 1, 2); all state vectors here are \
real, so no conjugation is needed when forming projectors.\
", "Text"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["1. The state", "Section"],

Cell["\
Inside each qutrit define a logical qubit |0_L> = |0>, |1_L> = (|1> + \
|2>)/Sqrt[2].  Define two orthonormal vectors in the logical 2x2 subspace:

    phi = (|0_L 0_L> + |1_L 1_L>)/Sqrt[2],
    chi = (|0_L 0_L> - |1_L 1_L>)/Sqrt[3] - (|0_L 1_L> + |1_L 0_L>)/Sqrt[6],

and the rank-two mixed state rho = (9/10) |phi><phi| + (1/10) |chi><chi|.  \
The first cell clears every symbol owned by this notebook, then defines the \
binary entropy h2 and the tensor-product helper kv \
(Flatten[TensorProduct[...]] gives the 9-vector |u>|v>; note \
KroneckerProduct of two plain vectors would give a matrix instead).  \
Expected output of the second cell: {1, 1, 0} (both normalized, mutually \
orthogonal).\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
ClearAll[h2, kv, ket0, ket1, phi, chi, rho, traceOutB, traceOutA, rhoA, \
 rhoB, PiL, vnEntropy, SA, SB, SAB, IAB, omega, mub, bases, jointTable, \
 PZ, PX, Pexpected, cmi, IZ, delta, rhoFull, rhoAFull, rhoBFull, \
 PfullExpected, PZfull, PXfull, IABfull, gapFull, rowT, colT, \
 eigsABfull, eigsAfull, ratioFull, numFull, denFull, PM2, PM3, IM2, Is, \
 subsetSums, holevoAB, IZB, IXB];
h2[p_] := -p Log2[p] - (1 - p) Log2[1 - p];
kv[u_, v_] := Flatten[TensorProduct[u, v]];\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
ket0 = {1, 0, 0}; ket1 = {0, 1/Sqrt[2], 1/Sqrt[2]};
phi = (kv[ket0, ket0] + kv[ket1, ket1])/Sqrt[2];
chi = kv[ket0, ket0]/Sqrt[3] - (kv[ket0, ket1] + kv[ket1, ket0])/Sqrt[6] - kv[ket1, ket1]/Sqrt[3];
Simplify[{phi . phi, chi . chi, phi . chi}]\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
Expected: trace 1, rank 2, spectrum {9/10, 1/10, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0}.  \
Because phi and chi are orthonormal eigenvectors, S(AB) = h2(1/10) exactly.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
rho = 9/10 Outer[Times, phi, phi] + 1/10 Outer[Times, chi, chi];
{Simplify[Tr[rho]], MatrixRank[rho], Sort[Simplify[Eigenvalues[rho]], Greater]}\
", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2. Marginals and quantum mutual information", "Section"],

Cell["\
Both reduced states equal half the projector onto the logical qubit, \
Pi_L/2, with spectrum {1/2, 1/2, 0}: both pure components are maximally \
entangled on the logical support (the coefficient matrix A_chi of chi \
satisfies A_chi A_chi^dagger = I/2).  Hence S(A) = S(B) = 1 and

    I(A:B) = 2 - h2(1/10).

Expected outputs: {True, True}, then {1, 1}, then True twice.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
traceOutB[m_] := Table[Sum[m[[3 (a - 1) + b, 3 (ap - 1) + b]], {b, 3}], {a, 3}, {ap, 3}];
traceOutA[m_] := Table[Sum[m[[3 (a - 1) + b, 3 (a - 1) + bp]], {a, 3}], {b, 3}, {bp, 3}];
rhoA = Simplify[traceOutB[rho]]; rhoB = Simplify[traceOutA[rho]];
PiL = Outer[Times, ket0, ket0] + Outer[Times, ket1, ket1];
{rhoA === Simplify[PiL/2], rhoB === Simplify[PiL/2]}\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
vnEntropy[m_] := Total[(-# Log2[#]) & /@ DeleteCases[Simplify[Eigenvalues[m]], 0]];
SA = Simplify[vnEntropy[rhoA]]; SB = Simplify[vnEntropy[rhoB]];
SAB = Simplify[vnEntropy[rho]];
{SA, SB}\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
{FullSimplify[SAB - h2[1/10]] === 0,
 FullSimplify[(IAB = SA + SB - SAB) - (2 - h2[1/10])] === 0}\
", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["3. The measurements are genuinely mutually unbiased", "Section"],

Cell["\
Take the qutrit computational basis Z and the Fourier basis X, i.e. the \
m = 0 member of the standard prime-dimension MUB family

    |v^m_k> = 3^(-1/2) Sum_j omega^(j k + m j^2) |j>,   omega = e^(2 Pi I/3).

The cell below checks all four qutrit MUBs at once (computational plus m = \
0, 1, 2; the extra two are used in Section 7): every cross-basis overlap \
satisfies |<u|v>|^2 = 1/3, so any two distinct bases in the list are \
mutually unbiased in the full ambient qutrit space, exactly as the \
conjecture's hypothesis requires.  Expected output: True.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
omega = Exp[2 Pi I/3];
mub[m_] := Table[omega^(j k + m j j)/Sqrt[3], {j, 0, 2}, {k, 0, 2}];
bases = {IdentityMatrix[3], mub[0], mub[1], mub[2]};
Union[Flatten@Table[
    FullSimplify[ComplexExpand[# Conjugate[#] &[
       Conjugate[bases[[p, All, i]]] . bases[[q, All, j]]]]],
    {p, 4}, {q, p + 1, 4}, {i, 3}, {j, 3}]] === {1/3}\
", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["4. Exact joint probability tables and classical mutual information", "Section"],

Cell["\
Measure the same basis on both sides.  jointTable conjugates rho by U \
tensor U and reads the diagonal.  Both the Z and X tables equal the exact \
rational matrix

    {{29/60, 1/120, 1/120}, {1/120, 29/240, 29/240}, {1/120, 29/240, 29/240}}

with marginals {1/2, 1/4, 1/4} on each side.  Expected outputs: {True, \
True}, then the marginals.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
jointTable[r_, U_] := Module[{V = KroneckerProduct[U, U], rr},
   rr = ConjugateTranspose[V] . r . V;
   Table[FullSimplify[ComplexExpand[rr[[3 (a - 1) + b, 3 (a - 1) + b]]]], {a, 3}, {b, 3}]];
PZ = jointTable[rho, IdentityMatrix[3]];
PX = jointTable[rho, mub[0]];
Pexpected = {{29/60, 1/120, 1/120}, {1/120, 29/240, 29/240}, {1/120, 29/240, 29/240}};
{PZ === Pexpected, PX === Pexpected}\
", "Input"],

Cell["{Total[PZ, {2}], Total[PZ]}", "Input"],

Cell["\
Coarse-graining outcomes 1 and 2 on each side gives a uniform-input binary \
symmetric channel with crossover 1/30, and the split of the coarse outcome \
into two physical outcomes is an independent fair coin on each side \
(29/240 = (29/60)/4, 1/120 = (1/60)/2), which adds no mutual information.  \
Hence I(Z^A:Z^B) = I(X^A:X^B) = 1 - h2(1/30).  The cell verifies this \
identity exactly from the table.  Expected output: True.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
cmi[P_] := Module[{ra = Total[P, {2}], cb = Total[P]},
   Sum[If[P[[i, j]] === 0, 0, P[[i, j]] Log2[P[[i, j]]/(ra[[i]] cb[[j]])]], {i, 3}, {j, 3}]];
IZ = cmi[PZ];
FullSimplify[IZ - (1 - h2[1/30])] === 0\
", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["5. The violation and its integer certificate", "Section"],

Cell["\
The CQC deficit is

    delta = 2 (1 - h2(1/30)) - (2 - h2(1/10)) = h2(1/10) - 2 h2(1/30),

and 30 delta = Log2[29^58/(3^114 10^30)], so delta > 0 is equivalent to the \
integer inequality 29^58 > 3^114 10^30 -- no floating point needed.  \
Expected outputs: {True, True, True}, then delta ~ 0.0473109929522169 bits.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
delta = FullSimplify[2 (1 - h2[1/30]) - (2 - h2[1/10])];
{FullSimplify[delta - (h2[1/10] - 2 h2[1/30])] === 0,
 FullSimplify[30 delta - Log2[29^58/(3^114 10^30)]] === 0,
 29^58 > 3^114 10^30}\
", "Input"],

Cell["N[delta, 30]", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["6. Not a rank-boundary artifact", "Section"],

Cell["\
Add 1% white noise: rho_full = (99/100) rho + (1/100) I/9.  The state \
becomes full rank with exact spectrum {8029/9000, 901/9000, 1/900 (x7)}, \
marginal spectrum {299/600, 299/600, 1/300}, and both measurements give

    {{8633/18000, 337/36000, 337/36000},
     {337/36000, 8693/72000, 8693/72000},
     {337/36000, 8693/72000, 8693/72000}}.

The violation persists: the gap is ~ 0.0369567802161937 bits > 0.  So the \
violating set has an open full-rank neighborhood.  Expected outputs: the \
spectra as stated, then {True, True, the displayed table, positive gap}.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
rhoFull = 99/100 rho + 1/100 IdentityMatrix[9]/9;
{Sort[Simplify[Eigenvalues[rhoFull]], Greater], MatrixRank[rhoFull]}\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
rhoAFull = Simplify[traceOutB[rhoFull]];
Sort[Simplify[Eigenvalues[rhoAFull]], Greater]\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
PfullExpected = {{8633/18000, 337/36000, 337/36000},
 {337/36000, 8693/72000, 8693/72000},
 {337/36000, 8693/72000, 8693/72000}};
PZfull = jointTable[rhoFull, IdentityMatrix[3]];
PXfull = jointTable[rhoFull, mub[0]];
IABfull = 2 vnEntropy[rhoAFull] - vnEntropy[rhoFull];
gapFull = FullSimplify[cmi[PZfull] + cmi[PXfull] - IABfull];
{PZfull === PfullExpected, PXfull === PfullExpected, PZfull, N[gapFull, 30]}\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
The full-rank gap also has an exact integer certificate.  Every \
probability and eigenvalue above is rational, and 72000 P_ij, 72000 mu (mu \
a marginal eigenvalue), and 36000 lambda (lambda a joint eigenvalue) are \
all integers, so 2^(36000 gap_full) assembles term by term into an \
explicit rational N/D with integer exponents only:

    36000 gap_full = Log2[N/D].

In prime-factor form,

    N = 2^35960 5^35720 89^34532 97^34532 337^2696 8693^34772,
    D = 7^104356 17^3604 31^32116 37^32116 43^72240 53^3604.

The cell builds the entropy ratio directly from the entropy terms, proves that it equals this \
explicit N/D, and checks N > D by exact integer comparison.  N and D have \
315504 and 315103 digits.  Expected output: \
{True, True, True, {315504, 315103}}.  (Do not print ratioFull itself -- \
it is a ~630000-digit rational.)\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
rowT = Total[PZfull, {2}]; colT = Total[PZfull];
eigsABfull = DeleteCases[Simplify[Eigenvalues[rhoFull]], 0];
eigsAfull = DeleteCases[Simplify[Eigenvalues[rhoAFull]], 0];
numFull = 2^35960 5^35720 89^34532 97^34532 337^2696 8693^34772;
denFull = 7^104356 17^3604 31^32116 37^32116 43^72240 53^3604;
ratioFull = Together[
   Times @@ Flatten[Table[(PZfull[[i, j]]/(rowT[[i]] colT[[j]]))^(72000 PZfull[[i, j]]), {i, 3}, {j, 3}]]*
    Times @@ ((#^(-36000 #)) & /@ eigsABfull)*
    Times @@ ((#^(72000 #)) & /@ eigsAfull)];
{Head[ratioFull] === Rational, ratioFull === numFull/denFull,
 numFull > denFull, IntegerLength /@ {numFull, denFull}}\
", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["7. Supplement: the other two MUBs, ECQC, and Iqbal's sufficient condition", "Section"],

Cell["\
The remaining two qutrit MUBs (m = 1, 2) yield identical exact tables \
{{11/60, 19/120, 19/120}, {19/120, 11/240, 11/240}, {19/120, 11/240, \
11/240}} carrying only ~ 0.0519 bits each.  Iqbal's extended conjecture \
ECQC (Conjecture 3.1 of arXiv:2509.08286) bounds the minimum over size-3 \
subsets of the four per-MUB classical mutual informations by I(A:B); the \
minimizing subset sums to ~ 0.893 < I(A:B) ~ 1.531, so ECQC survives this \
counterexample -- even though the subset {Z, X, M2} sums to ~ 1.630 > \
I(A:B).  Expected outputs: True; then {min-subset-sum, I(A:B), \
ECQC-satisfied, some-subset-exceeds} = {0.893..., 1.531..., True, True}.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
PM2 = jointTable[rho, mub[1]];
PM3 = jointTable[rho, mub[2]];
PM2 === PM3 === {{11/60, 19/120, 19/120}, {19/120, 11/240, 11/240}, {19/120, 11/240, 11/240}}\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
IM2 = cmi[PM2];
Is = {IZ, IZ, IM2, IM2};
subsetSums = Total[Is[[#]]] & /@ Subsets[Range[4], {3}];
N[{Min[subsetSums], IAB, Min[subsetSums] < IAB, Is[[1]] + Is[[2]] + Is[[3]] > IAB}, 20]\
", "Input"],

Cell["\
Consistency with proven results.  Iqbal's Proposition-3 sufficient \
condition I(Z^A:B) - I_Z + I(X^A:B) - I_X >= Log2[3] - S(A) provably \
implies CQC, so it must fail here -- and it does: LHS ~ 0.0233 < RHS ~ \
0.5850.  The proven Coles-Piani bound I(Z^A:B) + I(X^A:B) <= Log2[3] - \
S(A|B) holds with slack ~ 0.5143.  (The Holevo quantities I(M^A:B) need \
eigenvalues of conditional 3x3 blocks; they are evaluated from the exact \
matrices at 40-digit precision.)  Expected output: {0.0233..., 0.5850..., \
True, 0.5143...}.\
", "Text"],

Cell["\
holevoAB[r_, U_] := Module[{rr, acc = 0, blk, p},
   rr = ConjugateTranspose[KroneckerProduct[U, IdentityMatrix[3]]] . r . KroneckerProduct[U, IdentityMatrix[3]];
   Do[blk = rr[[3 (a - 1) + 1 ;; 3 a, 3 (a - 1) + 1 ;; 3 a]];
    p = Simplify[Tr[blk]];
    If[p =!= 0,
     acc += p Total[(-# Log2[#]) & /@
         DeleteCases[Chop[Eigenvalues[N[blk/p, 40]]], x_ /; Abs[x] < 10^-35]]],
    {a, 3}];
   vnEntropy[traceOutA[r]] - acc];
IZB = holevoAB[rho, IdentityMatrix[3]];
IXB = holevoAB[rho, mub[0]];
N[{IZB - IZ + IXB - IZ, Log2[3] - SA,
   IZB - IZ + IXB - IZ < Log2[3] - SA,
   Log2[3] - (SAB - SB) - (IZB + IXB)}, 20]\
", "Input"]

}, Open]],

Cell["\
Summary.  For this state, I(Z^A:Z^B) + I(X^A:X^B) = 2 - 2 h2(1/30) ~ \
1.5783 exceeds I(A:B) = 2 - h2(1/10) ~ 1.5310 by h2(1/10) - 2 h2(1/30) ~ \
0.0473 bits, certified by the integer inequality 29^58 > 3^114 10^30.  The \
state is mixed and its marginals are not maximally mixed.  Section 7 checks \
the Coles-Piani bound, Iqbal's sufficient condition, and ECQC; the \
accompanying status note documents the remaining established cases and \
bounds.  The mechanism: measurements mutually unbiased on \
the full qutrit cease to be complementary when compressed to the aligned \
logical-qubit support, so the two classical mutual informations count \
overlapping logical correlation twice.  See research/cqc-counterexample.md \
and research/cqc-status.md in this repository for the derivation and the \
literature status.\
", "Text"]

},
StyleDefinitions -> "Default.nb"
]
